entry.title: Winter Weather Advisory issued January 31 at 10:59AM AKST until February 1 at 11:00AM AKST by NWS Anchorage AK
entry.summary:
* WHAT...Blowing snow occurring. Total snow accumulations of 1 to 3 inches. Winds gusting as high as 45 mph.
* WHERE...Pribilof Islands.
* WHEN...Until 11 AM AKST Thursday.
* IMPACTS...Plan on difficult travel conditions. Areas of blowing snow could significantly reduce visibility.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Blowing snow will reduce visibility to one half mile or less for Saint Paul Island through early this afternoon. There may be a break in the worst conditions this afternoon before more falling snow moves in with stronger winds reaching Saint Paul later this evening into Thursday morning. Blowing snow is also possible for Saint George Island. However, temperatures closer to freezing will likely limit the intensity of any blowing snow. Temperatures are expected to warm into the lower to mid 30s by late Thursday morning, allowing for a mix of rain/snow and ending any potential for blowing snow.

The declaration of a Mandatory curtailment, when forecast indicate elevated levels of fine particulate air pollution in the region, is issued to protect the public health. Smoke from wood burning can cause health problems. The Mandatory Curtailment rule prohibits the operation of any wood burning appliance during the curtailment period. This prohibition does not apply to cookstoves and those devices exclusively gaseous- fueled.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued January 31 at 3:44AM MST by NWS Albuquerque NM
entry.summary:
..NEXT WINTER STORM TO BRING MOUNTAIN SNOW AND WIND FROM THURSDAY NIGHT INTO SATURDAY NIGHT...
After several days of tranquil weather and relatively warm temperatures, notable changes are in store for Thursday night into Saturday night as a vigorous disturbance and associated cold front sweep east across the region. Good chances for precipitation begin Thursday evening across western New Mexico and spread eastward through the daytime hours on Friday. Snow levels will start off high...nearly 9000 feet...but crash to valley floors on Friday night into Saturday morning, though precipitation coverage also decreases during this time. A little snow may mix in late Friday night for the Albuquerque metro area, but no accumulation is expected, whereas a dusting is possible for Santa Fe.
At the same time, precipitation is forecast to become more focused across the western and northern mountains, especially southern and western-facing slopes, where snow amounts may exceed one foot in the highest elevations of the Jemez mountains. Storm totals of 5 to 9 inches are likely for the Chuska, Sangre de Cristo, and portions of the Gila National Forest.
Breezy to gusty winds on Friday strengthen further for Saturday and Saturday night, with noticeably colder conditions taking hold as well. West winds along and east of the central mountain chain may gust up to 55-60mph, especially south of Interstate 40. Winds will gradually begin to subside later Saturday night, but may remain gusty until around mid-day Sunday.
Monitor NOAA weather radio, weather.gov/abq or your local media for the latest updates on this situation.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued January 30 at 8:14PM AKST by NWS Fairbanks AK
entry.summary:
Interior valley locations will fall back to -40 F to -50 F (some Interior cold spots will reach into the -55 F range, including Tanana, Fort Yukon, Coldfoot and Wiseman, and Arctic Village) for overnight lows. High temps will struggle to warm much beyond -30 F. Even the higher elevation Hills will fall back to near -40 F for low temps. This second significant cold snap will last through Saturday night before a gradual moderation in temperatures next week as the arctic low exits back into Canada.
Residents should prepare as needed for yet another old-fashioned Interior Alaska cold snap and have necessary cold weather gear available.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued January 30 at 2:49PM PST by NWS Seattle WA
entry.summary:
Rainfall of one to five inches over the past few days has increased soil moisture to high levels across western Washington. Heavy rainfall of up to 1 to 3 inches is expected through Wednesday, especially in the higher elevations.
This amount of rain will put extra pressure on soil instability, leading to an increased threat of landslides.
Two landslides have already been reported in various locations in western Washington including the Leschi neighborhood in Seattle and near Union. More landslides are possible.
For more information about current conditions, visit www.weather.gov/seattle, select Hydrology, and then scroll down for the links to the landslide information pages.
For more information on landslides, visit the website for the Washington State Department of Natural Resources landslide geologic hazards at: http://bit.ly/2mtA3wn

Winds will pick up by late Wednesday morning, then travel conditions will begin to worsen late Wednesday afternoon and evening, with the most widespread winter travel impacts likely from Wednesday evening through much of Thursday.
* WHAT...Heavy snow expected. Snow accumulations 10 to 20 inches above 7000 feet, with 20 to 30 inches near the Sierra crest. Below 7000 feet, 5 to 10 inches are expected, except up to 16 inches west of CA-89. Winds gusting as high as 45 mph, with gusts around 100 mph for Sierra ridges. Wave heights 2 to 4 feet on Lake Tahoe Wednesday and Wednesday night.
* WHERE...Greater Lake Tahoe Area.
* WHEN...From 10 AM Wednesday to 10 AM PST Friday. Heaviest snow is most likely from Wednesday evening through Thursday morning.
* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible with snowfall rates of 2 or more inches per hour at times. Hazardous conditions will impact the commutes from Wednesday evening through Friday morning. Strong winds may blow down some tree limbs and a few power outages may result.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Winds will increase late Wednesday morning, with snow developing by late afternoon near the Sierra crest passes. Snow levels will start between 6500 and 7000 feet Wednesday, then drop to near Lake Tahoe level Wednesday night and all Tahoe area valleys by Thursday morning.
